<p>It would seem that you have two options: use a small number of weights and get low accuracy (TensorFlow‚Äôs logistic regression example) or use 100,000\(^+\) weights and get 99\(^+\)% accuracy (the PyTorch example is a notable exception). I think this leads to a common misconception that the best way to gain a few percentage points in accuracy is to double the size of your model.</p>

<p><strong>MNIST lite</strong>. I was interested in how slightly smaller models would perform on the MNIST task, so I built and trained a few:</p>

